wiki.text:
A theory of 'substantial forms' asserts that forms (or ideas) organize matter
and make it intelligible. Substantial forms are the source of properties, order,
unity, identity, and information about objects.

The idea of substantial forms dominates ancient Greek philosophy and medieval
philosophy, but has fallen out of favour in modern
philosophy.<ref>[http://www.anselmphilosophy.com/substance/ David Banach. What
Killed Substantial Form?]</ref> The idea of substantial forms has been abandoned
for a mechanical, or “bottom-up” theory of
organization.<ref>[http://www.anselm.edu/library/SAJ/pdf/51Hill.pdf Benjamin
Hill. Substantial Forms and the Rise of Modern Science]</ref>
